# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bill-virdon
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The **1955 major league baseball season** began on April 11, 1955.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 25, with the Brooklyn Dodgers and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 52nd World Series on September 28 and ended with Game 7 on October 4.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] In the sixth iteration of this Subway Series World Series matchup, The Dodgers defeated the Yankees, four games to three, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first World Series between the two teams to see the Dodgers win over the Yankees.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Giants from the 1954 season.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The 22nd All-Star Game was held on July 12 at Milwaukee County Stadium in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, home of the Milwaukee Braves.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] In a continuation of the relocation trend that began in 1953, a team moved for the third consecutive year.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The Athletics moved from Philadelphia to Kansas City, Missouri, leaving Philadelphia as a one-team city.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] On April 14, the New York Yankees became the 13th team to break baseball's color line when they called up Elston Howard.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The 1955 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 11, featuring four teams.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 25, which saw all sixteen teams play, the first time since 1953.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between September 28 and October 4.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] 3 tie games (2 in AL, 1 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles had two tie games.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Sox and Kansas City Athletics had one tie game each.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Dodgers and Chicago Cubs had one tie game each.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on September 28 and ended on October 4 with the Brooklyn Dodgers defeating the New York Yankees in the 1955 World Series in seven games.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] With the relocation of the Philadelphia Athletics from Philadelphia, Pennsylvania to Kansas City, Missouri as the Kansas City Athletics, they leave Connie Mack Stadium (where they played 46 seasons) and move into Municipal Stadium.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] They would go on to play there for 13 seasons through 1967, before again relocating.
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The *Game of the Week* moved from ABC to CBS (the rights were actually set up through the Falstaff Brewing Corporation).
[src:bill-virdon/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The All-Star Game and World Series aired on NBC.
[src:bill-virdon/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The **1956 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1956.
[src:bill-virdon/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 30, with the Brooklyn Dodgers and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-virdon/1956-major-league-baseball-season] In a rematch of the previous season, the postseason began with Game 1 of the 53rd World Series on October 3 and ended with Game 7 on October 10.
[src:bill-virdon/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The series is notable for Yankees pitcher Don Larsen's perfect game in Game 5.
[src:bill-virdon/1956-major-league-baseball-season] In the seventh iteration of this Subway Series World Series matchup (and a rematch of the previous year), the Yankees defeated the Dodgers, four games to three, capturing their 17th championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1953.
[src:bill-virdon/1956-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the final Subway Series matchup between the two teams, as the next World Series between the two in 1963 would see a relocated Dodgers franchise in Los Angeles, California.
[src:bill-virdon/1956-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Brooklyn Dodgers from the 1955 season.
[src:bill-virdon/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The 23rd All-Star Game was held on July 10 at Griffith Stadium in Washington, D.C., home of the Washington Senators.
[src:bill-virdon/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The 1956 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-virdon/1956-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 17, featuring all sixteen teams, the first time since 1954.
[src:bill-virdon/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 30, which also saw all sixteen teams play, continuing the trend from the previous season.
[src:bill-virdon/1956-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first time since 1950 that all sixteen teams played their first and last games on the same days.
[src:bill-virdon/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 3 and October 10.
[src:bill-virdon/1956-major-league-baseball-season] 7 tie games (2 in AL, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-virdon/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Red Sox, Cleveland Indians, Detroit Tigers, and Washington Senators had one tie game each.
[src:bill-virdon/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Cubs and Pittsburgh Pirates had three tie games each.
[src:bill-virdon/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Redlegs and Milwaukee Braves had one tie game each.
[src:bill-virdon/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 3 and ended on October 10 with the New York Yankees defeating the Brooklyn Dodgers in the 1956 World Series in seven games.
[src:bill-virdon/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Dodgers began playing several home games in Jersey City, New Jersey, playing seven games on April 19, May 16, June 25, July 25, 31, August 7 and 15.
[src:bill-virdon/1956-major-league-baseball-season] CBS aired the Saturday *Game of the Week* for the second consecutive year.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] The **1960 Pittsburgh Pirates season** was the team's 79th season.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] The team finished with a record of 95–59, seven games in front of the second-place Milwaukee Braves to win their first National League championship in 33 seasons.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] The team went on to play the heavily favored New York Yankees, whom they defeated 4 games to 3 in one of the most storied World Series ever.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] At the 1959 Winter Meetings, Pirates general manager Joe L.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] Brown had agreed to trade Dick Groat to the Kansas City Athletics in exchange for Roger Maris.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] Pirates manager Danny Murtaugh had advised Brown that he did not want to lose Groat, and the deal was never finalized.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] Maris was eventually traded to the Yankees, and both players would go on to win the MVP for their respective leagues and face each other in the World Series.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] On September 6, team captain Dick Groat was drilled on his left wrist by an inside pitch from Braves pitcher Lew Burdette.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] Groat was lost for the rest of the season.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] Dick Schofield stepped in for the injured Groat and went three for three in that September 6 game.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] The Pirates won the game 5–3 and Schofield would go on to hit .414 for the rest of the season.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] On September 25 in Milwaukee, the Pirates clinched their first pennant in 33 years.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] The 1960 Pirates team, which featured eight All-Stars, was widely predicted to lose the World Series to a powerful New York Yankees team.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] October 5, 1960, at Forbes Field in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] October 6, 1960, at Forbes Field in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] October 8, 1960, at Yankee Stadium in New York City.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] October 9, 1960, at Yankee Stadium in New York City.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] October 10, 1960, at Yankee Stadium in New York City.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] October 12, 1960, at Forbes Field in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] October 13, 1960, at Forbes Field in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The **1960 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 1960 season.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The 57th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff that matched the National League (NL) champion Pittsburgh Pirates against the American League (AL) champion New York Yankees.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] In Game 7, Bill Mazeroski hit the series winning ninth-inning home run, the first time a winner-take-all World Series game ended with a home run, and the first World Series to end on a home run.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Mazeroski's home run gave the Pirates their third title overall and their first since 1925.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Despite losing the series, the Yankees scored 55 runs, the most runs scored by any one team in World Series history, and more than twice as many as the Pirates, who scored 27.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The Yankees won three blowouts (16–3, 10–0, and 12–0), while the Pirates won four close games (6–4, 3–2, 5–2, and 10–9) to win the series.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The Pirates' run differential of minus 28 is the lowest ever by any team, winner or loser, in a World Series.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The Series MVP was Bobby Richardson of the Yankees, the only time in history that the award has been given to a member of the losing team, though the rules were different at this time.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Votes had to be in by the start of the 8th inning of Game 7, at which point the Yankees were in the lead, and this was the first time since the series MVP award was created in 1955 that the team leading at that point did not go on to win.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Richardson was also the first non-pitcher to be named MVP.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] This World Series featured seven past, present, or future league Most Valuable Players.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The Yankees, winners of their 10th pennant in 12 years, outscored the Pirates 55–27 in this Series, out-hit them 91–60, out-batted them .338 to .256, hit 10 home runs to Pittsburgh's four (three of which came in Game 7), got two complete-game shutouts from Whitey Ford—and lost.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The Pirates' inconsistent pitching and Yankees' manager Casey Stengel's controversial decision not to start Ford in Games 1 and 4 resulted in the peculiar combination of close games and routs.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Ford (Games 3 and 6) and Vern Law (Games 1 and 4) were excellent, while Pirates relief pitcher Roy Face was a major factor in Games 1, 4 and 5.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The Yankees also committed twice as many errors as the Pirates in the series.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The Yankees had 8 errors while the Pirates had four errors.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The Yankees threw Art Ditmar against the Pirates' Vern Law (the NL Cy Young Award winner) in Game 1.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] In the top of the first inning, New York right fielder Roger Maris, the eventual 1960 AL MVP, drilled a home run off Law to give the Yankees a 1–0 lead.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] In the bottom half, however, the Pirates evened the score when Bill Virdon walked, stole second, advanced to third on an error by shortstop Tony Kubek, and scored on a double by eventual National League Most Valuable Player Dick Groat.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Bob Skinner then singled to drive in Groat and stole second, coming home on a single by Roberto Clemente.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] This was enough to compel Casey Stengel, the Yankee manager, to pull Ditmar in favor of Jim Coates, who finished the inning.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] In the fourth, New York cut the lead to one run when Maris singled, moved to second on a Mickey Mantle walk, took third on a fly out by Yogi Berra, and scored on a single by Bill Skowron.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] But the Pirates extended their lead to 5–2 in the fourth when Don Hoak walked and Bill Mazeroski homered.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Game 2, matching New York's Bob Turley against the Pirates' Bob Friend, saw the Yankees pummel Pittsburgh 16–3.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The game was scoreless until the top of the third, when the Yankees jumped out to a 2–0 lead.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Second baseman Bobby Richardson walked, was sacrificed over to second by Turley, and scored on a single by Tony Kubek.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Gil McDougald then doubled, plating Kubek all the way from first base.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Turley aided his own cause with an RBI single in the fourth, driving home Richardson, who had singled and moved to second on a passed ball.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Although Hoak doubled home Gino Cimoli in the bottom of the fourth to break the shutout, the Yankees extended their lead to 5–1 courtesy of a two-run home run by Mantle off Fred Green.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] In the sixth, the solid Yankee lead turned into a rout.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Elston Howard hit a lead-off triple and scored on Bobby Richardson's double to chase Green from the game.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] A passed ball by Smoky Burgess and error by shortstop Dick Groat on Tony Kubek's ground ball put runners on first and third with one out before McDougald's RBI single made it 7–1 Yankees.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] After a walk and strikeout, Yogi Berra's two-run single and Bill Skowron's RBI single made it 10–1 Yankees.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Red Witt relieved Labine and allowed back-to-back RBI singles to Howard and Richardson that made it 12–1 Yankees.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Mantle continued the onslaught by blasting a three-run home run in the seventh off Joe Gibbon and scoring on a wild pitch by Tom Cheney in the ninth after walking and moving to third on a double, making it 16–1 Yankees.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Although the Pirates tacked on two runs in the bottom half of the frame on back-to-back RBI singles by Gino Cimoli and Smoky Burgess, Bobby Shantz relieved Turley and got Don Hoak to hit into the game-ending double play.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] This decisive Yankee victory tied the series at a game apiece.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] For Game 3, the Series shifted to Yankee Stadium as Stengel sent Whitey Ford to the mound against Pittsburgh's Vinegar Bend Mizell.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Ford had somewhat of an off year (12–9, 3.08 ERA and 192.2 IP) for his lofty standards, but was brilliant against the Pirates.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The Yankees continued the offensive onslaught they displayed in Game 2, grabbing a 6–0 lead by the end of the first inning.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] After two singles, Bill Skowron drove in the first run with an RBI single.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] After a walk loaded the bases, Elston Howard added another run with an RBI single off Clem Labine before Bobby Richardson capped the scoring with a grand slam (during the regular season, Richardson had hit only one home run, off Baltimore's Arnie Portocarrero on April 30).
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The next time a first inning World Series Grand slam would be hit would be in the 2021 World Series, 61 years later.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] In the fourth, the Bronx Bombers added on four more runs, courtesy of a two-run home run by Mickey Mantle off Fred Green and—after three singles had loaded the bases—a two-run single by Richardson off Red Witt.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The Pirates, meanwhile, could not get anything going against Ford, who tossed a masterful four-hitter.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The Pirates had seen their pitching fail them in the last two games, as the team fell victim to the powerful Yankee bats.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] This was not the case in Game 4, however, as Pittsburgh sent Game 1 winner Vern Law to the hill against Ralph Terry.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The game was scoreless until the bottom of the fourth, when Bill Skowron launched a home run off Law to give New York a 1–0 advantage.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The very next half-inning, though, Pittsburgh stormed back, when with two on and two outs, Law doubled in Gino Cimoli to tie the game and Bill Virdon's two-run single put the Pirates up 3–1.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Law kept the potent pinstripers at bay, though the Yankees did scratch and claw for a single run in the bottom of the seventh when Skowron doubled, moved to third on a single by McDougald, and scored on a fielder's choice on a ball hit by Richardson.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] After a pinch-hit single by Johnny Blanchard, Pirate manager Danny Murtaugh brought in reliever Roy Face, who held the fort for the final 2+2⁄3 innings as Pittsburgh tied the series at two games apiece to ensure a return to Forbes Field.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] As it turned out, on this day Ditmar could not get out of the second inning once again.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Dick Stuart singled and was forced out at second on a fielder's choice hit by Gino Cimoli, who then moved to third on a double by Smoky Burgess.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Don Hoak then slapped a ground ball toward Yankee shortstop Tony Kubek, who flipped it to third baseman Gil McDougald in an attempt to retire Burgess, who was attempting to advance.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] However, McDougald dropped the ball for an error (Kubek's toss was accurate), allowing Cimoli to score, with Burgess safe at third, and Hoak reaching second on the error.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Bill Mazeroski then lashed a double to left, scoring Burgess and Hoak.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] After this offensive outburst, Stengel yanked Ditmar and replaced him with Luis Arroyo, who finally ended the inning and stranded Mazeroski.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The next half-inning, New York picked up a run when Elston Howard doubled, moved to third on a ground-out by Bobby Richardson, and scored on another grounder by Kubek.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] However, the Pirates extended their lead back to three runs in the third, when Roberto Clemente singled home Groat, who led off with a double.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] In the bottom of the third, Roger Maris touched Haddix for a home run to deep right field.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Otherwise, however, the Pittsburgh hurler was in fine form, holding the Yankees at bay until the seventh, when he was replaced by Face.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] In the ninth, the Pirates added an insurance run off Ryne Duren.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Smoky Burgess had singled and taken second on an error; he was replaced at second by pinch-runner Joe Christopher, who moved to third on a wild pitch, and was singled in by Hoak.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Face then shut down the Yankees once again to give the Pirates a 5–2 victory and 3–2 series lead.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] For the sixth contest in Pittsburgh, the Yankees started Whitey Ford against the Pirates' Bob Friend.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] And as was the case the last time Ford had toed the rubber for the Yanks in Game 3, his teammates relentlessly mashed the ball, en route to a resounding 12–0 victory.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] In the top of the second, the Yankees went to work.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] After a Yogi Berra walk and a Bill Skowron single, Elston Howard was hit by a pitch to load the bases (Eli Grba ran for him).
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Ford himself then notched the first RBI of the game, with a ground ball single to his counterpart Friend that scored Berra.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The next inning, after a lead-off hit-by-pitch and double, Mantle cracked a two-run single that scored Tony Kubek and Roger Maris.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] After a Yogi Berra single moved Mantle to third, Pirates skipper Danny Murtaugh removed the clearly ineffective Friend in favor of Tom Cheney.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Cheney, however, fared no better, as a Bill Skowron sacrifice fly scored Mantle and, after a single, a Richardson triple to deep left field scored Berra and Johnny Blanchard, making the score 6–0.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The Yankees then ran away with the game, scoring two runs in each of the sixth, seventh, and eighth innings.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] In the sixth, Clete Boyer hit a lead-off triple off Fred Green and scored on Kubek's single.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] After another single, Berra's RBI single off Clem Labine made it 8–0 Yankees.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Next inning, after a lead-off double by Blanchard, Richardson ripped his second RBI triple of the contest, and Ford added his second RBI courtesy of a fielder's choice on a sacrifice bunt.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] In the eighth, Berra hit an RBI single with a runner on second, and later scored on Blanchard's double.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] As in Game 3, Ford was his masterful self, not letting the Pirates mount anything resembling a rally for the full nine innings.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] His second shutout of the series was critical, as it forced Game 7.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Yankee manager Casey Stengel would come under fire in Mickey Mantle's autobiography for letting Ford finish this game—instead of removing him once the Yankees had a comfortable lead—thus making him unavailable out of the bullpen if needed in Game 7.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] For the deciding seventh game, Bob Turley, the winning pitcher in Game 2, got the nod for the Yankees against the Pirates' Vern Law, the winning pitcher in Games 1 and 4.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Turley lasted only one inning plus one batter.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] After retiring the first two batters, Turley walked Bob Skinner, then first baseman Rocky Nelson homered, Pittsburgh's first home run since Bill Mazeroski's in Game 1, to give the Pirates a 2–0 lead.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Turley was then pulled after giving up a single to Smoky Burgess leading off the second.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Don Hoak then drew a walk against Bill Stafford, and a bunt single by Mazeroski loaded the bases.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Stafford appeared to get the Yankees out of trouble after inducing Law to hit into a double play, pitcher to catcher to first.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] But lead-off man Bill Virdon's single to right scored Hoak and Mazeroski and increased the Pirates' lead to 4–0.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The Yankees got on the board in the fifth on Bill Skowron's lead-off home run, his second of the Series.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] In the sixth, Bobby Richardson led off with a single and Tony Kubek drew a walk.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Elroy Face relieved Law and got Roger Maris to pop out to Hoak in foul territory, but Mickey Mantle singled to score Richardson.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Face then blew the save when Yogi Berra followed with a three-run shot to right that gave the Yankees their first lead, 5–4.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The Yankees extended their lead to 7–4 in the eighth with two more runs off Face.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] With two out, Berra walked, and Skowron singled when the Pirates couldn't get a force-out.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Johnny Blanchard (who had replaced Elston Howard at catcher for game 7) then singled to score Berra, and Clete Boyer doubled to score Skowron.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] But the Pirates retook the lead with a 5-run eighth inning.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Gino Cimoli (pinch-hitting for Face) led off with a single, and Virdon hit a ground ball to short for what could have been a double play.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] But the ball instead took a bad hop and hit Kubek in the throat, leaving everybody safe and knocking the wind out of Kubek.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] He eventually got up, and game footage showed him arguing with manager Stengel, seemingly insisting he was ok to stay in the game.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] He was eventually coaxed off the field and replaced.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] He was taken to a hospital and kept overnight for observation due to concerns surrounding his trachea swelling up and thus, causing difficulty breathing.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Back on the field, Dick Groat then chased Bobby Shantz (who had entered the game in the third and had pitched five innings, having not pitched more than four in any game during the regular season) with a single to score Cimoli and send Virdon to second.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Jim Coates relieved Shantz and got Skinner out on a sacrifice bunt, which moved the runners up.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Nelson followed with a fly ball to right, and Virdon declined to challenge Maris' throwing arm.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The high chopper allowed Virdon to score, cutting the Yankee lead to 7–6.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Hal Smith, who had replaced Smoky Burgess at catcher after being pinch-run for by Joe Christopher followed with a three-run home run to give the Pirates a 9–7 lead.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Game 4 loser Ralph Terry relieved Coates and got the last out.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Bob Friend, an 18-game winner for the Pirates and their starter (and loser) in Games 2 and 6, came on in the ninth to try to protect the lead.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Bobby Richardson and pinch-hitter Dale Long both greeted him with singles, and Pirates manager Danny Murtaugh was forced to remove the veteran pitcher in favor of Harvey Haddix.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Although he got Roger Maris to foul out, Haddix gave up a key single to Mickey Mantle that scored Richardson and moved Long to third.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Yogi Berra followed, hitting a sharp grounder to first, with Rocky Nelson easily getting the second out.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Had Mantle been out on the play, the run would likely not have counted since the play happened so quickly that the runner on third might not have crossed the plate before the out was recorded.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] With Mantle safe, the inning continued, but ended when Bill Skowron hit into a force play.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Ralph Terry returned to the mound in the bottom of the ninth.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The first batter to face him was Bill Mazeroski.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] As the Pirates erupted, the Yankees stood across the field in stunned disbelief.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The improbable champions were outscored, out-hit, and outplayed, but somehow had managed to pull out a Game 7 victory.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Years later, Mickey Mantle was quoted in Ken Burns' documentary *Baseball* as saying that losing the 1960 series was the only loss, amateur or professional, he cried actual tears over.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] For Bill Mazeroski, by contrast, his Series-clinching home run was the highlight of a Hall of Fame career otherwise notable mostly for excellent defense.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Mazeroski became the first player to end the World Series with a home run.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Thirty-three years later, Joe Carter would become the only other player to end a World Series with a home run, doing so for the Toronto Blue Jays in the 1993 World Series against the Pirates' in-state rivals, the Philadelphia Phillies, albeit in Game 6.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Because of the game’s back-and-forth nature (especially in the eighth and ninth innings) and historic conclusion, the game is considered by some to be the greatest game in MLB history, as well as one of the greatest games in the history of professional sports.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Although most noted for the series-ending homer, Game 7 is also the only game in all of postseason history with no strikeouts recorded by either side.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Bobby Richardson of the Yankees was named MVP of the Series, the only time someone from the losing team has been so honored.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] He batted .367 with 12 RBIs and eight runs in the Series and hit the key grand slam in Game 3.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Prior to the mid-1970s, television networks and stations generally did not preserve their telecasts of sporting events, choosing instead to tape over them.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] As a result, the broadcasts of the first six games are no longer known to exist.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The lone exception is a black-and-white kinescope of the entire telecast of Game 7, which was discovered in a wine cellar in Bing Crosby's former home in Hillsborough, California, in December 2009.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] A part-owner of the Pirates who was too superstitious to watch the Series live, Crosby listened to the decisive contest with his wife Kathryn and two friends on a shortwave radio in Paris, France.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Wanting to watch the game at a later date only if the Pirates won, he arranged for the telecast to be recorded by Ampex, in which he also held a financial investment.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] After viewing the kinescope, he placed it in his wine cellar, where it sat untouched for 49 years.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] It was finally found by Robert Bader, vice-president of marketing and production for Bing Crosby Enterprises, while looking through videotapes of Crosby's television specials which were to be transferred to DVD.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The five-reel set is the only known complete copy of the historic game, which was originally broadcast in color.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The NBC television announcers for the Series were Bob Prince and Mel Allen, the primary play-by-play voices for the Pirates and Yankees respectively.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Prince called the first half of Game 7 and conducted post-game interviews in the Pittsburgh clubhouse, while Allen did the latter portion of the game.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] On October 13, 2010, for the 50th anniversary of the series winning home run, a gala was hosted by the Byham Theater in downtown Pittsburgh, where the historic telecast of Game 7 was re-aired in its entirety.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] Bill Virdon, 1960 MVP Dick Groat and Yankee Bobby Richardson were guest speakers, with actor and Pittsburgh native Jeff Goldblum hosting the event.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The MLB Network would air the game and gala on December 15, 2010.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The telecast was also released on DVD by A&E Home Video.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] To date, the Pirates are the only team to win a seven-game postseason series while being out-scored by 28 runs or more.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] This would prove to be Casey Stengel's last World Series, as the Yankees soon sent him into retirement.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] This led to his famous remark, "I'll never make the mistake of turning 70 again." Mazeroski and Clemente were the last two remaining Pirates players from the 1960 World Series winners along with manager Danny Murtaugh and third-base coach Frank Oceak, when the Pirates won the World Series in 1971.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] To date, this is the last championship in any of the four major sports to be won in Pittsburgh by the home team, as the Pirates' two subsequent World Series championships in 1971 and 1979, both against the Baltimore Orioles, were clinched at Memorial Stadium.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The Pittsburgh Penguins have won all five of their Stanley Cup titles on the road, and the Pittsburgh Steelers have won all six of their Super Bowl championships at neutral sites, as is customary in the NFL.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] The Yankees returned to the World Series the following year and the year after, and won back-to-back championships over the Cincinnati Reds and San Francisco Giants in five and seven games respectively.
[src:bill-virdon/1960-world-series] In 2025, the NBC radio broadcast of Game 7 by Chuck Thompson was selected by the Library of Congress for preservation in the National Recording Registry.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] The **1965 major league baseball season** began on April 12, 1965.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 3, with the Los Angeles Dodgers and Minnesota Twins as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 62nd World Series on October 6 and ended with Game 7 on October 14.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] The Dodgers defeated the Twins, four games to three, capturing their fourth championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1963.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the St.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] The 36th All-Star Game was held on July 13 at Metropolitan Stadium in Bloomington, Minnesota, home of the Minnesota Twins.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] The Houston Colt .45s became the Houston Astros, as they moved from Colt Stadium to the new Astrodome, becoming the first team to play their home games indoors, rather than outdoors.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] It was also the final season for the Milwaukee Braves, before relocating to Atlanta, Georgia and becoming the Atlanta Braves for the 1966 season.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] The Los Angeles Angels officially changed their name to California Angels on September 2, 1965, with only 28 games left in the season, in advance of their pending 1966 move to a new stadium in Anaheim, California.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] In June, the first Major League Baseball draft was held in New York City.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] Teams chose players in reverse order of the previous season's standings, with picks alternating between American League and National League teams.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] With the first pick of the 1965 MLB draft, the Kansas City Athletics took Rick Monday, an outfielder from Arizona State University.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] This was Ford Frick's last season of his 14-year tenure as Commissioner of Baseball, as he resigned following the season's end on November 16.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] US Army LTG William Eckert was elected and took office on November 17.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] The 1965 schedule consisted of 162 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had 10 teams.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 18 games against the other nine teams of their respective league.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place by the American League since the 1961 season and by the National League since the 1962 season, and would be used until 1969.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 12, featuring 16 teams.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 3, which saw all 20 teams play.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 6 and October 14.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] 4 tie games (0 in AL, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Cubs and New York Mets had two tie games each.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Phillies, Pittsburgh Pirates, San Francisco Giants, and St.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 6 and ended on October 14 with the Los Angeles Dodgers defeating the Minnesota Twins in the 1965 World Series in seven games.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] The Houston Colt .45s open the Houston Astrodome (and aptly rename as the Houston Astros) after playing at Colt Stadium for three seasons.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] The team would play at the Houston Astrodome for 35 seasons through 1999.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] The Milwaukee Braves would play their final game at Milwaukee County Stadium on September 22 against the Los Angeles Dodgers, relocating to Atlanta, Georgia at Atlanta Stadium as the Atlanta Braves for the start of the 1966 season.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] The California Angels would play their final two games at Dodger Stadium on September 22 in a doubleheader against the Boston Red Sox, moving into Anaheim Stadium for the start of the 1966 season.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] In 1965, ABC provided the first-ever nationwide baseball coverage with weekly Saturday broadcasts on a regional basis.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] ABC paid $5.7 million for the rights to the 28 Saturday/holiday *Games of the Week*.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] ABC's deal covered all of the teams except the New York Yankees and Philadelphia Phillies (who had their own television deals) and called for two regionalized games on Saturdays, Independence Day, and Labor Day.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] ET games and one game for the Pacific Time Zone at 5 p.m.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] Although MLB ended the *Game of the Week* blackouts in cities with MLB clubs, ABC blacked out the games in the home cities of the clubs playing those games.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, CBS continued to air its own slate of *Games of the Week* with the rights to individual teams, with its New York Yankees games in particular beating ABC in the ratings.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] At the end of the season, ABC declined to exercise its $6.5 million option for 1966, citing poor ratings, especially in New York.
[src:bill-virdon/1965-major-league-baseball-season] Although it did not air *Games of the Week* this season, NBC continued to air the All-Star Game and World Series.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The **1968 major league baseball season** began on April 10, 1968.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 29, with the St.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals and Detroit Tigers as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 65th World Series on October 2 and ended with Game 7 on October 10.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] In the second iteration of this World Series matchup, the Tigers defeated the Cardinals, four games to three, capturing their third championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1945.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The 39th All-Star Game was held on July 9 at the Houston Astrodome in Houston, Texas, home of the Houston Astros.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The Kansas City Athletics moved to Oakland, California as the Oakland Athletics, being the eighth team since 1953 to relocate, and the fourth of American League teams since them.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] Kansas City would be without a major league team for the 1968 season.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] Legal pressure from the city moved the originally planned 1971 American League expansion up to 1969, which saw the enfranchisement of the Kansas City Royals.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The 1968 schedule consisted of 162 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had 10 teams.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place by the American League since the 1961 season and by the National League since the 1962 season.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the last season with this format, as the following season would see a new format due to expansion and the creation of divisions.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 10, featuring all 20 teams in both leagues.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 29, which saw all teams play, except for the Baltimore Orioles and Cleveland Indians.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 2 and October 10.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (3 in AL, 3 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Tigers and New York Yankees had two tie games each.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Indians and Oakland Athletics had one tie each.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The Atlanta Braves, Chicago Cubs, Cincinnati Reds, New York Mets, Pittsburgh Pirates, and San Francisco Giants had one tie each.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 2 and ended on October 10 with the Detroit Tigers defeating the St.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals in the 1968 World Series in seven games.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] With the relocation of the Kansas City Athletics from Kansas City, Missouri to Oakland, California as the Oakland Athletics, they leave Municipal Stadium (where they played 13 seasons) and move into Oakland–Alameda County Coliseum.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] They would go on to play there for 57 seasons through 2024, before again relocating.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Sox began playing select games in the former home of the Milwaukee Braves in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, at Milwaukee County Stadium, hosting nine of 81 home games, on May 15, 28, June 17, 24, July 11, 22, August 2, 8, and 26.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] Though only 11% of home games, these nine games accounted for 33% of all home games attendance for the White Sox.
[src:bill-virdon/1968-major-league-baseball-season] NBC was the exclusive national TV broadcaster of MLB, airing the weekend *Game of the Week*, the All-Star Game, and the World Series.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] The **1971 National League Championship Series** was a best-of-five series in Major League Baseball’s 1971 postseason that pitted the East Division champion Pittsburgh Pirates against the West Division champion San Francisco Giants.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Pirates won the Series three games to one and won the 1971 World Series against the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Giants did not return to the postseason until 1987.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] This was the third National League Championship Series in all.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] It was the first League Championship Series in either league that was not a sweep for the winning team (Baltimore swept Oakland in the 1971 ALCS).
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] With aces Gaylord Perry and Steve Blass taking the mound for their respective teams, Game 1 looked to be a pitchers' duel.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Pirates struck for two in the top of the third when Dave Cash doubled home Jackie Hernández.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] Cash scored the second run when Richie Hebner grounded to Tito Fuentes at second, but Willie McCovey dropped Fuentes' throw when he attempted to field the ball after having to scramble back to first because Perry didn't cover the bag.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Giants halved the lead in their half of the third when Chris Speier singled, went to second on a Perry sacrifice bunt, and scored on a Ken Henderson single.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] Fuentes and McCovey would redeem themselves in the fifth by each slamming two-run homers off Blass for a 5–2 lead.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] Al Oliver cut the deficit to 5–4 for the Pirates with two-run single in the seventh, but that was it as Perry went the distance for a complete game win.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] In front of an NBC-TV audience, Pirate first baseman Bob Robertson grew into a star in Game 2.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] Robertson smashed three homers, becoming the first to do so in a playoff game.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Giants struck first in the bottom of the first when Tito Fuentes singled off Dock Ellis and scored on a double by Willie Mays.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] After the Pirates tied the game in the second off John Cumberland when Robertson hit a leadoff double and scored on Manny Sanguillén's single, the Giants retook the lead in the bottom half when Chris Speier hit a leadoff double and scored on Ken Henderson's single.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] Robertson's first home run of the game tied the score again in the fourth.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] Sanguillén's single then knocked Cumberland out of the game.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] After a stolen base, Jackie Hernández's RBI single off Jim Barr put the Pirates up 3–2.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] Gene Clines's home run next inning extended their lead to 4–2.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] A pivotal play occurred just prior to the Pirates' 4-run seventh, when Mays, batting in the bottom of the sixth with two out and his team trailing, 4–2, saw his bid for a bases-clearing double grabbed by right fielder Roberto Clemente.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] After a leadoff double and single, Clemente's RBI single off Don Carrithers made it 5–2 Pirates.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] One out later, Robertsons' three-run home run off Ron Bryant extended their lead to 8–2.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] Robertson's third home run in the ninth off of Steve Hamilton made it 9–2.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] A two-run home run from Mays off Bob Miller in the bottom half made it 9–4, but Dave Giusti in relief retired all three batters he faced as the Pirates tied the series heading to Pittsburgh.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Pirates' Bob Johnson and the Giants' Juan Marichal locked into a tight pitcher's duel for eight innings.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] Bob Robertson hit a homer in the second, his then-record fourth of the series.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Giants tied it in the sixth when Ken Henderson singled and scored when third baseman Richie Hebner threw wildly past Robertson at first after fielding a bunt by Tito Fuentes.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] Hebner would atone for the error, however, by slamming a game-winning homer in the eighth off Marichal.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] Dave Giusti came on in the ninth and saved it for Johnson and the Pirates.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] Another anticipated pitching duel between Giants' Gaylord Perry and Pirates' Steve Blass quickly went by the wayside.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] Blass lasted only two innings, giving up five runs.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] Willie McCovey's RBI single with two on in the first gave the Giants a 1–0 lead, but they left the bases loaded.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] In the bottom half, after a leadoff single and double, Roberto Clemente's two-run single put the Pirates up 2–1, but in the second, Chris Speier's leadoff home run tied the game.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] After two singles and two outs, Willie McCovey's three-run home run put the Giants up 5–2, but the Pirates, however, got Blass off the hook in the bottom of the inning.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] Manny Sanguillen singled and 1960 World Series hero Bill Mazeroski, hitting for Blass, also singled.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] Richie Hebner then tied the game with a three-run home run.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] The score stayed at 5–5 until the sixth when Dave Cash singled, moved to second on a groundout, and scored on a Roberto Clemente RBI single.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] Jerry Johnson relieved Perry and after intentionally walking Willie Stargell, Al Oliver's three-run home run made it 9–5 Pirates.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] Meanwhile, Bruce Kison and Dave Giusti pitched the last seven innings of shutout baseball to close out the series and win the pennant for the first time in 11 years.
[src:bill-virdon/1971-national-league-championship-series] It is Pittsburgh’s fifth-most recent victory in a postseason series.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] After playing in the minors for the Yankees organization, Virdon was traded to the Cardinals, and he made his MLB debut in 1955.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] That year, Virdon won the National League Rookie of the Year Award.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] He slumped at the beginning of the 1956 season, and was traded to the Pirates, where he spent the remainder of his playing career.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] A premier defensive outfielder during his playing days as a center fielder for the Cardinals and Pirates, Virdon led a strong defensive team to the 1960 World Series championship.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Following the 1965 season, he retired due to his desire to become a manager.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon managed in the minor leagues until returning to the Pirates as a coach in 1968.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] He served as manager of the Pirates in 1972 and 1973, before becoming the manager of the Yankees in 1974.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] During the 1975 season, the Yankees fired Virdon, and he was hired by the Astros.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] After being fired by the Astros after the 1982 season, Virdon managed the Expos in 1983 and 1984.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon won *The Sporting News*' Manager of the Year Award in 1974, his only full season working for the Yankees, and in 1980, while managing the Astros.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] He returned to the Pirates as a coach following his managerial career, and remained with the Pirates as a guest instructor during spring training.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] William Charles Virdon was born in Hazel Park, Michigan, on June 9, 1931.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] His parents, Bertha and Charles Virdon, were originally from Missouri, but moved to Hazel Park during the Great Depression, where they were able to find jobs in automotive factories.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] When he was 12 years old, his family moved to West Plains, Missouri.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon attended West Plains High School.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] He competed in American football, basketball, and track and field for the school.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] As West Plains did not compete in baseball, Virdon traveled to Clay Center, Kansas, to play for their American Amateur Baseball Congress team as a center fielder and shortstop.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] He enrolled at Drury University in Springfield, Missouri.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon attended an open tryout held by the New York Yankees in Branson, Missouri, and scout Tom Greenwade signed Virdon to the Yankees for a $1,800 signing bonus ($24,087 in current dollar terms).
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon made his professional debut in 1950 with the Independence Yankees in the Class D Kansas–Oklahoma–Missouri League, and was promoted to the Kansas City Blues in the Class AAA American Association for the final 14 games of the season.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon played for the Norfolk Tars in the Class B Piedmont League in 1951, and for the Binghamton Triplets in the Class A Eastern League in 1952.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] The Yankees assigned him to Kansas City in 1953, but he struggled, batting .233.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] While he played in Kansas City, Virdon was diagnosed with astigmatism.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] When Kansas City manager Harry Craft noticed Virdon reading while wearing glasses, Craft told him to wear them while he played.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] The Yankees demoted Virdon to the Birmingham Barons in the Class AA Southern Association.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] In 42 games for Birmingham, Virdon had a .317 batting average.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] According to Hal Smith, his roommate with Birmingham, Virdon changed his approach to hitting, prioritizing line drives to all parts of the field, rather than trying to hit for power.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon remained stuck behind Mickey Mantle on the Yankees' depth chart for center field, while Gene Woodling and Hank Bauer played the corner outfield positions.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Louis Cardinals before the 1954 season with Mel Wright and Emil Tellinger for veteran outfielder and All-Star Enos Slaughter.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon struggled during spring training, and Cardinals manager Eddie Stanky worked with Virdon to improve his hitting.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] The Cardinals assigned Virdon to the Rochester Red Wings of the Class AAA International League for the season.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] He led the league with a .333 batting average and hit 22 home runs, finishing second in voting for the International League Most Valuable Player Award to catcher Elston Howard with the Toronto Maple Leafs Baseball Club.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon joined the Cardinals in 1955, as the Cardinals moved Stan Musial to first base to allow Virdon to play the outfield.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] As a rookie, Virdon had a .281 average with 17 home runs and 69 runs batted in (RBIs).
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] He was named the winner of the National League (NL) Rookie of the Year Award, voted on by the Baseball Writers' Association of America, beating Jack Meyer of the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] After the 1955 season, the Cardinals hired Frank Lane, nicknamed "The Trader", as their general manager.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon slumped to begin the 1956 season, and the Cardinals traded him to the Pittsburgh Pirates in May 1956 for Bobby Del Greco and Dick Littlefield.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Lane claimed that Virdon's late season slump in 1955 was because he tired down the stretch, and that is why he chose to trade him.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Lane later referred to the trade as "the worst trade [he] ever made".
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] When he arrived at Pittsburgh, he developed an eye condition, for which he received treatment, missing one week of the season.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon's vision improved, and he challenged Hank Aaron for the NL batting title.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon batted .334 for the Pirates during remainder of the season, which increased his season batting average to .319, second-best in the NL to Aaron, who batted .328.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Pirates' announcer Bob Prince gave Virdon the nickname "Quail" due to the frequency of his soft-hit infield hits.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] The Pirates hired Danny Murtaugh as their manager during the 1957 season; Virdon credited Murtaugh with pushing him to perform at his best.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon consistently batted in the .260s for the next several seasons.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] He led all NL center fielders in assists in 1959 with 16, and in double plays turned with five.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] In 1960, Virdon, along with right fielder Roberto Clemente, shortstop Dick Groat, second baseman Bill Mazeroski, and third baseman Don Hoak, formed a strong defensive unit for the Pirates, and they reached the 1960 World Series, where they faced the New York Yankees.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon batted .241 during the seven-game series.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] In the deciding Game 7, he hit a ground ball that struck Yankees shortstop Tony Kubek in the throat after taking an unpredictable bounce, enabling Virdon to reach base safely.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] This started a rally for the Pirates that culminated in Bill Mazeroski's home run that won the series for Pittsburgh.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon led the NL in triples with 10 during the 1962 season.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] That year, he won the Rawlings Gold Glove Award.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] He struggled in the 1964 season, batting only .243.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Though his batting average improved to .279 in the 1965 season, Virdon retired after the season due to his desire to become a manager.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon retired with 1,596 MLB hits and a career batting average of .267 with 91 home runs during his 1,583-game NL career.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon hit an impressive .404 (21-for-52) against Sandy Koufax, the highest average of any batter facing the legendary Hall of Fame pitcher.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon began operating a baseball academy in 1956.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] After the 1962 season, Virdon coached in the Arizona Instructional League.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] He coached in the Florida Instructional League following the 1964 season.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Following his retirement as a player after the 1965 season, Virdon spent the next two seasons as a manager in the minor leagues for the New York Mets' organization.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] In 1966, he managed the Williamsport Mets of the Eastern League, and in 1967, he managed the Jacksonville Suns of the International League.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] He led Williamsport to a 68–72 win–loss record, and Jacksonville to a 66–73 record.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon joined the Pirates' major league coaching staff under manager Larry Shepard in 1968.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] He also appeared in six games as a player because a number of Pirates players had entered military service.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Shepard left the Pirates after the 1969 season, and Virdon interviewed to become the Pirates' next manager.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] However, the Pirates re-hired Murtaugh, and Virdon remained on Murtaugh's coaching staff.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon coached for the Pirates as they won the 1971 World Series.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Due to health problems, Murtaugh retired after the 1971 season, and Virdon was named as his successor.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] As a manager, Virdon led the Pirates to the 1972 NL East division title, but the Pirates lost the 1972 National League Championship Series (NLCS) to the Cincinnati Reds when Pittsburgh pitcher Bob Moose unleashed a wild pitch in the final inning of Game 5, allowing the winning run to score.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] The 1973 Pirates now played without Clemente, who died during the previous offseason.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Further struggles included pitcher Steve Blass' inability to throw strikes and injuries to Dock Ellis.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon clashed with Ellis and Richie Hebner.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] The Pirates were in third place with a 67–69 record when the team fired Virdon and replaced him with Murtaugh.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] The Yankees announced the hiring of Dick Williams as their manager for the 1974 season, but American League president Joe Cronin nullified the transaction because Williams was still under contract with the Oakland Athletics.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] The Athletics demanded prospects Otto Vélez and Scott McGregor as compensation for Williams, but the Yankees decided the price was too steep.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Without a manager, the Yankees hired Virdon, signing him to a one-year contract.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon led the Yankees to a competitive finish, one game behind the Baltimore Orioles in the American League East division.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] He won *The Sporting News*' Manager of the Year Award.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] The Yankees signed him to a two-year contract after the 1974 season, with a raise from $50,000 to $65,000 per year.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] However, Virdon clashed with Bobby Murcer.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] He received a death threat due to his preference of playing Elliott Maddox over Murcer in center field.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] When Billy Martin was fired as manager of the Texas Rangers during the 1975 season, the Yankees fired Virdon on August 2 and hired Martin.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] With Yankee Stadium being renovated in the two years he was at the helm (the club played at Shea Stadium instead), Virdon became the only Yankees manager (post-1923) to never manage a game at the Yankees’ venerable ballpark.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] The Houston Astros hired Virdon as their manager on August 20, 1975, succeeding Preston Gómez.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Tal Smith, who had served as executive vice president for the Yankees, had become the Astros' general manager on August 7.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon led the Astros to third-place finishes in 1976 and 1977, but the Astros slipped to fifth place in 1978.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] The 1979 Astros fell one game short of winning the NL West division championship.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] The Astros tied the Los Angeles Dodgers for the division championship in 1980, and defeated them in the 1980 NL West tie-breaker game.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] The Astros played the Philadelphia Phillies in the 1980 NLCS that went the full five games that saw the final four end in extra innings while Houston blew an eighth inning lead in both Game 4 and Game 5, each held at home.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] He again won the Manager of the Year Award in 1980.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Due to the 1981 Major League Baseball strike, the 1981 season was split into halves with each half's winner appearing in the 1981 NL Division Series.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] The Dodgers won the first half, while the Astros won the second.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] In the Division Series, the Astros won the first two games at home, each in extra innings.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] They then went to Los Angeles needing one more win.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] However, the Astros scored two runs combined in the next three games to lose the series.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] During the 1982 season, the Astros fell to fifth place with a disastrous 9-14 first month that had them go below .500 by the fifth game and never recover.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Beset by injuries to relievers Joe Sambito and Dave Smith that each saw them miss significant time, the Astros lost over a dozen games in late innings.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] On August 11, Virdon was fired during the season and replaced by Bob Lillis.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] The Montreal Expos hired Virdon as their manager before the 1983 season, replacing Jim Fanning, and signed him to a two-year contract.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] During the 1984 season, Virdon expressed to Expos general manager John McHale that he did not want to return to the Expos in 1985.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] With a 64–67 record in August 1984, the Expos fired Virdon, replacing him with Fanning.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Gary Lucas, a pitcher for the Expos, felt that they had lost many one-run games because Virdon was too conservative in his managing, not employing the hit and run play and relying on the starting pitcher for too long into the game.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon returned to the Pirates as the hitting coach under Jim Leyland in 1986, Leyland's first season as a manager.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] He took the position only when he was convinced that he would not succeed Leyland should the Pirates fire him.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Following a contract dispute, the Pirates replaced Virdon with Milt May before the 1987 season.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon remained with the Pirates as a minor league hitting instructor from 1987 through 1989.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] He worked as a spring training instructor for the Cardinals in 1990 and 1991, and then rejoined Leyland's coaching staff in Pittsburgh in 1992.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] With Major League Baseball expanding by two teams for the 1993 season, in 1992 Virdon interviewed for the managerial positions of both expansion teams, the Florida Marlins and the Colorado Rockies.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] The Marlins instead hired Rene Lachemann, and the Rockies hired Don Baylor.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] In 1994, Virdon interviewed with the Orioles for their vacant managerial position.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon left the Pirates after the 1995 season.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] He became the bench coach for the Astros under first-time manager Larry Dierker in 1997.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] The Pirates brought Virdon back as their bench coach for the 2001 season under first-time manager Lloyd McClendon.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] He retired from coaching after the 2002 season.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon's career managerial record, over all or parts of 13 seasons, was 995–921 (.519).
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] He also managed in the minor leagues for the Cardinals and the Astros.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] In June 2012, the Pirates attempted to add Virdon and Mazeroski to their coaching staff, but were rebuffed by MLB for violating the rules on uniformed coaching staffs after one game.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon continued to serve as a special outfield instructor for the Pirates during spring training.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon and his wife, Shirley, married in November 1951, and lived in Springfield, Missouri.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Together, Bill and Shirley Virdon endowed two scholarships at Southeast Missouri State University, Shirley's alma mater, with one specifically devoted to a baseball player.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Route 63 business route in West Plains from Grace Avenue to US 63 is named "Bill Virdon Boulevard".
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon was inducted into the Missouri Sports Hall of Fame in 1983, and named a Missouri Sports Legend by the Missouri Sports Hall of Fame in 2012.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] The Independence Baseball Hall of Fame inducted Virdon in 2013.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Following Whitey Herzog's election to the National Baseball Hall of Fame in 2010, Herzog indicated that he would champion Virdon's cause to the Veterans Committee in future elections.
[src:bill-virdon/bill-virdon] Virdon died on November 23, 2021, at the age of 90.
